{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503102"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:55:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:55:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1933"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1933"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.2,0.62,0.06,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1933"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81689"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1933"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1933"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66988"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"6061"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1831"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81689"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following a motor vehicle accident with fractures of his left femur and left humerus. He undergoes open reduction and internal fixation. Two days after admission, he becomes confused and cyanosed. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 110/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 32/min, SpO2 85% on room air, and temperature 39.7\u00b0C. There are petechiae on his neck, chest and axillary regions. His urine output has decreased over the past four hours. Chest examination reveals bilateral crackles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArterial blood gas on room air shows pH 7.45, PaO2 40 mmHg (80-100), PaCO2 27 mmHg (35-45). Chest X-ray shows diffuse bilateral infiltrates, which was normal on admission.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary contusion","Acute respiratory distress syndrome","Fat embolism syndrome","Pulmonary embolism","Hospital-acquired pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of fat embolism syndrome: respiratory insufficiency, neurological symptoms (confusion), and petechial rash. \u003Cstrong\u003EFat embolism syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs 24-72 hours after long bone fractures, particularly of the femur. The diagnosis is made using Gurd\u0027s criteria, which includes major criteria (petechial rash, respiratory symptoms with bilateral infiltrates, and neurological symptoms) and minor criteria (tachycardia, fever, retinal changes, jaundice, and renal dysfunction).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary contusion\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents immediately after trauma and would have been evident on the initial chest X-ray. The delayed onset of symptoms and the presence of petechiae make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute respiratory distress syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can occur following trauma but typically develops within hours of the initial insult. While the bilateral infiltrates are consistent with ARDS, the presence of petechiae and the timing strongly favour fat embolism syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E from deep vein thrombosis typically occurs 5-7 days post-operatively. While it can cause hypoxia and tachycardia, it would not explain the petechial rash or the bilateral infiltrates on chest X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHospital-acquired pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E usually develops after 48 hours of hospitalisation but typically presents with localised rather than diffuse infiltrates. The presence of petechiae and the pattern of respiratory compromise are inconsistent with pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fat embolism syndrome classically presents 24-72 hours after long bone fractures with the triad of respiratory distress, neurological symptoms, and petechial rash.","Gurd\u0027s criteria are used to diagnose fat embolism syndrome, with petechial rash being a pathognomonic feature.","The timing of presentation helps differentiate fat embolism syndrome from other post-traumatic respiratory complications."],"references":["Mellor A, Soni N. Fat embolism. Anaesthesia. 2001;56: 145-154.","Glover P, Worthley LI. Fat embolism. Crit Care Resusc. 1999 Sep;1:276-84.","Levy D. The Fat Embolism Syndrome A Review. Clin Orthop Relat Res. 1990 Dec;261:281-286.","Amandeep Gupta, Charles S. Reilly, Fat embolism, Continuing Education in Anaesthesia Critical Care \u0026 Pain, Volume 7, Issue 5, October 2007, Pages 148\u2013151, https://doi.org/10.1093/bjaceaccp/mkm027"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66988"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1933"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66988"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T19:54:50+10:30","up